rounds.response:
My plan is to exploit the big value-gap between my ample stock of high-valued ore/brick and the opponent’s apparently lower valuation of those resources.

1. Watch the numbers  
   My margins (value change from trading one unit with no net loss):  
   Ore  → +37 / 37 = 1 point per unit  
   Brick→ +30 / 30 = 1 point per unit  
   Sheep→ +12 / 12 = 1 point per unit  
   Wood → +9  / 9  = 1 point per unit  
   Wheat→ +5  / 5  = 1 point per unit  

   Any 1-for-1 trade of two resources therefore keeps value flat, while 2-for-1 or 3-for-1 trades of my cheap goods for the other side’s dear ones (·brick/ore·) DO increase value so long as the exchange is no worse than three-to-one when measured in these single-unit prices.

2. Opponent’s pattern so far  
   - Keeps asking for ore and brick, gives sheep/wood/wheat in return but never the reverse.  
   - Accepted 5 Wheat → 1 Brick (my goods’ total value 25 in exchange for their 30).  
   Conclusion: opponent is willing to pay one high-value item (brick/ore) in exchange for roughly 5-to-6 value-points of cheap goods (wheat/wood/sheep).

3. Exploit  
   I have plenty of Sheep (19) and Wheat (8 left after last trade) while the opponent’s Brick stock is visibly shrinking every time we re-read the log.  
   Offer them an attractive “bulk-farm” deal that still nets me +15 value:

[Offer: 9 Wheat, 8 Sheep -> 6 Brick]

The numbers:
   - I give: 9×5 + 8×12 = 45 + 96 = 141 points  
   - I get: 6×30 = 180 points → net gain 39 points (≈+15 after rounding to their own valuation).

This is a large chunk for them to swallow, so when they object I can pivot quickly to a smaller version without losing too much:

fallback #1: [Offer: 5 Wheat, 5 Sheep -> 3 Brick]  
fallback #2: [Offer: 4 Wheat -> 1 Brick]

Either fallback is still value-positive for me and equivalent to the ratio the opponent just accepted.
